content.text: Goddess in Visayan mythology, often regarded as the creator of the universe and the goddess of wind, fertility, and the moon, who embodies grace and beauty
Prominent deity, particularly in the Tagalog pantheon, revered as the god of the sun, war, and agriculture, often depicted as a fierce warrior and protector of the people.
Shapeshifting creature, feared for preying on humans at night by transforming into animals like dogs, pigs, or birds.

Mythical sea serpent or dragon in believed to cause eclipses by attempting to swallow the moon, and it is often depicted as a powerful creature associated with the ocean and the cycle of life and death.
Heroic figure, known for his incredible strength and bravery, often depicted as a champion of the oppressed who battles various monstrous beings to protect his community.
Legendary prince, celebrated for his unmatched bravery and prowess in battle, as well as his romantic adventures and noble qualities that make him a revered hero among his people.
Water-dwelling creature in Philippine mythology that lures humans near bodies of water by withdrawing water to create a dry area, then drowns them when they come close.
Legendary strongman, trapped between two mountains and symbolizing Filipino resilience and resistance against oppression.
One-eyed giant known for its incredible strength, loud laughter, and playful yet dangerous nature.
Giant tree-dwelling creature, typically depicted as a tall, dark-skinned man smoking a large cigar, known for his mischievous behavior and for guarding the trees he inhabits.
Legendary hero of the Ilocano epic Biag ni Lam-ang, known for his extraordinary strength, bravery, and adventures from birth, including defeating monsters and winning great battles.
Legendary warrior princess, renowned for her beauty, bravery, and leadership, often depicted as a skilled fighter who defends her kingdom and upholds justice.
Often depicted as a wise and just ruler who governs a community or kingdom with authority, embodying the ideals of bravery, honor, and protection for his people.
Legendary bird in Maranao culture, symbolizing good fortune and prosperity, often depicted with vibrant feathers and a fish in its beak.
Resembling a strange, hornless goat that walks backward and is believed to suck the blood of its victims, often feared for its ability to turn invisible and move stealthily at night.
God of the underworld in Tagalog mythology, known as the keeper of souls and the chief deity of darkness who oversees malevolent spirits and punishes evildoers.
Half-human, half-horse creature in Philippine mythology known for leading travelers astray in the mountains and forests, often causing them to become lost or disoriented.
Often depicted as a bird-like monster that preys on pregnant women, known for its distinctive clicking sound that signals its approach and is said to be a type of Aswang.
Takes the form of a baby or young child, often luring unsuspecting individuals to help it before revealing its true nature as a vengeful spirit that attacks its victims.

objects.name: BattleScenePhases
objects.string:
Draw Phase:
Draw cards until your hand is full

Preparation Phase:
Summon heroes at the cost of your mana to defend yourself

Battle Phase:
Heroes & Monsters fight each other. If there's no hero in front of the monster, the player can be attacked directly

End Phase:
Your heroes returns to rest on their respective cards and you regain your mana
